const sourceCode = "# Issue Tracking\n\nClearSight tracks issues across crawls so you can see your accessibility progress over time.\n\n## How It Works\n\nEach issue gets a **deterministic hash** based on:\n- Rule ID (axe-core or custom engine)\n- Element selector\n- WCAG criterion\n- Page URL\n\nThe same violation on the same element on the same page produces the same hash — even across different crawls.\n\n## Issue Lifecycle\n\n```\nNew issue detected     → status: open\nSame issue next crawl  → status: open (recurring, lastSeenScanId updated)\nIssue disappears       → status: fixed\nUser dismisses         → status: dismissed (persists across crawls)\nUser marks can't fix   → status: cant_fix (persists across crawls)\n```\n\n## Crawl Comparison\n\nWhen a crawl completes, ClearSight compares issue hashes with the previous crawl:\n\n- **New issues** — hash exists in current crawl but not previous\n- **Fixed issues** — hash exists in previous crawl but not current (and was `open`)\n- **Recurring** — hash exists in both crawls\n\nThese counts are displayed on the crawl detail page.\n\n## Dismissing Issues\n\nFrom the Issues view, you can:\n\n- **Dismiss** — marks as \"not relevant.\" Hidden from default view but still detected by scanner. Status persists across future crawls.\n- **Can't Fix** — marks as \"acknowledged.\" Visible but muted. Persists across crawls.\n- **Reopen** — restores to `open` status.\n\nUse the \"Show dismissed\" toggle to view dismissed issues.\n\n## Status Carryover\n\nWhen you dismiss an issue and re-crawl:\n1. The scanner still detects the same element/rule violation\n2. ClearSight matches the hash to the previous crawl\n3. The `dismissed` or `cant_fix` status is automatically carried over\n4. The issue stays hidden/muted in the new crawl's results\n\nThis means you only need to dismiss an issue once.";
